</b></p>
<p> <b>5 
</b></p>
<p><b>Introduction 
</b></p>
<p>1. The present document is submitted by the Special Rapporteur on the situation of 
human rights defenders, Ms. Margaret Sekaggya, to the Human Rights Council, pursuant to 
resolutions 5/1 and 7/8 of the Human Rights Council. The document provides observations 
on the communications on specific cases addressed by the Special Rapporteur to States, as 
well as on the replies by States received. 
</p>
<p>2. The cases raised by the Special Rapporteur in this addendum include 
communications sent between 12 December 2010 and 30 November 2011.  
</p>
<p>3. The addendum contains observations on the communications and responses received 
from States until 31 January 2012. A few replies received before 31 January 2012 are not 
included in the present report because translation of these documents has not been finalised. 
Most of the responses by States refer to cases raised by the Special Rapporteur during the 
period December 2010 to November 2011; however, some of the responses are to cases 
addressed by her in earlier reporting periods. These communications are marked with a 
footnote in the text. 
</p>
<p>4. For ease of reference, cases have been grouped by country, with countries listed 
alphabetically according to their names in English. Each communication is referenced in 
one of four categories: urgent appeal (UA), allegation letter (AL), joint urgent appeal (JUA) 
and joint allegation letter (JAL). This is followed by the date the communication was 
issued, as well as the case number and the State reply. The electronic version of the present 
document has both of these items hyperlinked, and clicking on them will open the 
communication sent and the reply from the concerned State, respectively, as uploaded on 
the OHCHR website. Finally, in bold, is a summary of the allegations contained in the 
communication in the language of submission 
</p>
<p>5. The Special Rapporteur is grateful to all States which have transmitted responses to 
communications sent. She considers response to her communications an important part of 
cooperation by states with her mandate. 
</p>
<p><b>  Algeria  
</b></p>
<p>6. JAL 11/10/11   Case no.: DZA 4/2011   State Reply: 11/01/12   <b>Recrudescence 
</b>all&#233;gu&#233;e d&#8223;actes<b> de harc&#232;lement judicaire contre les membres de la Ligue Alg&#233;rienne 
</b></p>
<p>pour la D&#233;fense des Droits de l&#8223;Homme (LADDH) et des syndicalistes autonomes.  
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>7. La Rapporteuse sp&#233;ciale est pr&#233;occup&#233;e par les informations re&#231;ues faisant &#233;tat 
d&#8217;harc&#232;lement judiciaire &#224; l'encontre des d&#233;fenseurs des droits de l&#8217;homme en Alg&#233;rie. A 
cet &#233;gard, elle aimerait rappeler au Gouvernement de l&#8217;Alg&#233;rie l&#8217;article 2 et l&#8217;article 12 de 
la D&#233;claration sur les d&#233;fenseurs des droits de l&#8217;homme. 
</p>
<p>8. La Rapporteuse sp&#233;ciale a &#233;galement suivi le d&#233;veloppement visant &#224; l'adoption 
d'une nouvelle loi sur les associations en Alg&#233;rie durant la p&#233;riode couverte par le pr&#233;sent 
rapport. Afin d&#8217;assurer un cadre de travail favorable &#224; l'expression des d&#233;fenseurs des droits 
</p>
<p>de l&#8217;homme en Alg&#233;rie, elle aimerait attirer l&#8217;attention du Gouvernement sur l&#8217;article 5, 
</p>
<p>alin&#233;as b) et c) de la D&#233;claration sur les d&#233;fenseurs des droits de l&#8217;homme, ainsi que sur les 
</p>
<p>recommandations incluses dans son rapport &#224; l&#8217;Assembl&#233;e g&#233;n&#233;rale de 2009 (A/64/226), en 
</p>
<p>particulier ses para. 104 &#224; 116. </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/19/55/Add.2 
</b></p>
<p><b>6</b>  
</p>
<p><b>  Angola 
</b></p>
<p>9. JAL<b> </b>29/08/11   Case no.: AGO 2/2011   State Reply: None to date  <b> Alleged denial 
of entry by immigration officials.  </b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>10. The Special Rapporteur regrets that no reply has been received from the 
Government of Angola to the allegation letter sent during the reporting period upon 
finalization of the current report. The Special Rapporteur is concerned about information 
received on alleged restrictions on the right to freedom of peaceful assembly in Angola, 
including reported deportations of human rights defenders from neighbouring countries 
who had planned to attend the Southern Africa Civil Society Forum. In this regard, the 
Special Rapporteur wishes to refer the Government of Angola to the provisions of the 
Declaration on Human Rights Defenders, particularly article 5, points b) and c). 
</p>
<p><b>  Argentina 
</b></p>
<p>11. JUA 27/06/11   Case no.: ARG 2/2011   State Reply: 07/09/11    <b>Supuestas 
amenazas contra juez.</b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observaciones 
</b></p>
<p>12. La Relatora Especial se muestra preocupada por los actos de intimidaci&#243;n a 
defensores de los derechos humanos, en particular a jueces, abogados y funcionarios 
p&#250;blicos, que luchan contra la impunidad por cr&#237;menes de lesa humanidad ocurridos 
durante la dictadura militar. La Relatora Especial toma nota de que dicha denuncia, objeto 
de su comunicaci&#243;n, no habr&#237;a sido tramitada ante el Consejo de Magistratura. 
</p>
<p>13. La Relatora Especial desea hacer referencia al Gobierno de Argentina las 
provisiones contenidas en la Declaraci&#243;n sobre los defensores de derechos humanos, 
particularmente  el art&#237;culo 9, p&#225;rrafo 3, apartado c), el cual establece que toda persona 
tiene derecho, individual o colectivamente, entre otras cosas, a ofrecer y prestar asistencia 
letrada profesional u otro asesoramiento y asistencia pertinentes para defender los derechos 
humanos y las libertades fundamentales. 
</p>
<p><b>  Azerbaijan 
</b></p>
<p>14. JUA 16/03/11   Case no.: AZE 1/2011   State Reply: 05/05/11   <b>Alleged closure of 
human rights organisation. </b> 
</p>
<p>15. JUA 24/08/11   Case no.: AZE 2/2011   State Reply: 08/09/11   <b>Alleged demolition 
of a building owned by a human rights defender. </b> 
</p>
<p>16. JAL 27/09/11   Case no.: AZE 3/2011   State reply: None to date   <b>Alleged 
</b>destruction of women&#8223;s centre.  
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>17. The Special Rapporteur wishes to acknowledge the Government&#8217;s dialogue with the 
organizations involved in the situation outlined in one of the communications sent during 
the reporting period. Nevertheless, she remains concerned that the policies put in place to 
monitor NGOs might be putting unnecessary restrictions on the work of human rights 
defenders. The Special Rapporteur wishes to refer the Government of Azerbaijan to the 
recommendations put forward in her 2009 report to the General Assembly (A/64/226), </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/19/55/Add.2 
</b></p>
<p> <b>7 
</b></p>
<p>particularly para. 104 to 119. The Special Rapporteur remains available to provide any 
guidance or technical support the Government of Azerbaijan might require. 
</p>
<p><b>  Bahrain 
</b></p>
<p>18. JUA 17/02/11   Case no.: BHR 1/2011  State Reply: 05/04/11 <b>  Alleged excessive 
use of force in the context of peaceful protests.  
</b></p>
<p>19. JUA 18/03/11   Case no.: BHR 3/2011   State Reply: 20/04/11  <b>Alleged excessive 
use of force by security forces against protesters.  
</b></p>
<p>20. JUA 22/03/11   Case no.: BHR 4/2011   State Reply: 26/04/11<b>   Alleged arrests and 
threats against human rights defenders. </b> 
</p>
<p>21. JUA 12/04/11   Case no.: BHR 5/2011 State Reply: 07/06/11   <b>Alleged 
incommunicado detention and possible enforced disappearance. </b> 
</p>
<p>22. JUA 21/04/11   Case no.: BHR 6/2011  State Reply: 08/06/11<b>   Alleged arrest, 
detention and possible enforced disappearance of human rights lawyer. </b> 
</p>
<p>23. JUA 20/05/11   Case no.: BHR 9/2011   State Reply: 08/06/11   <b>Alleged torture 
and mistreatment in detention. </b> 
</p>
<p>24. JUA 16/06/11   Case no.: BHR 12/2011 State Reply: 29/08/11, 02/09/11   
<b>Allegations of acts of violence, intimidation, and the enactment of travel bans against, 
</b></p>
<p><b>as well as the interrogation of, a number of human rights defenders. </b> 
</p>
<p>25. JUA 04/07/11   Case no.: BHR 14/2011   State Reply: 24/08/11   <b>Alleged torture 
and ill-treatment of opposition politician. </b> 
</p>
<p>26. JUA 05/08/11   Case no.: BHR 17/2011   State Reply: 23/09/11   <b>Alleged life 
imprisonment of human rights defenders. </b> 
</p>
<p>27. JUA 09/09/11   Case no.: BHR 18/2011   State Reply: 15/12/11   <b>Alleged arrests, 
detention, harassment and stigmatisation against human rights defenders and their 
</b></p>
<p><b>relatives. </b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>28. The Special Rapporteur is concerned about the significant number of allegations 
received and communications sent during the reporting period. She is deeply concerned 
about the physical and psychological integrity of human rights defenders in Bahrain, in 
particular at the reported practice of detention in undisclosed locations as well as about 
their treatment while in detention.  She remains very concerned about the situation of Mr. 
Abdulhadi Al-Khawaja and Dr. Abduljalil Al-Singace, as well as their co-defendants, who 
were sentenced to life imprisonment on 22 June 2011. The Special Rapporteur is also 
concerned about the reported restrictions on the right to peaceful assembly and the right to 
freedom of opinion and expression in Bahrain. In this connection, the Special Rapporteur 
wishes to refer the Government of Bahrain to the provisions outlined in the Declaration on 
Human Rights Defenders, notably to article 2; article 5 point (a) and (b); to article 6 point 
(b) and (c); and to article 12, in particular para. 2 and 3. 
</p>
<p><b>  Bangladesh 
</b></p>
<p>29. JUA 14/03/11   Case no.: BGD 3/2011  State Reply: 02/04/11   <b>Alleged 
surveillance of human rights organization.</b> </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/19/55/Add.2 
</b></p>
<p><b>8</b>  
</p>
<p>30. JUA 10/06/11   Case no.: BGD 4/2011   State Reply: 14/06/11, 28/06/11   <b>Alleged 
abduction, interrogation and ill-treatment of human rights defender.</b> 
</p>
<p>31. JAL 11/10/11   Case no.: BGD 5/2011   State Reply: 12/10/11   <b>Alleged delay in 
approval for funding for NGO project.</b> 
</p>
<p>32. JUA 10/11/11   Case no.: BGD 6/2011   State Reply: 16/11/11<b>   Alleged acts of 
intimidation against human rights defender and teacher.  </b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>33. The Special Rapporteur thanks the Government of Bangladesh for the responses 
received to her communications sent during the reporting period, but she regrets that the 
allegations contained therein were not adequately addressed. The Special Rapporteur 
remains concerned about the reported restrictions on the right to association and the rights 
to freedom of opinion and expression in Bangladesh. In this connection, the Special 
Rapporteur wishes to refer the Government of Bangladesh to the provisions outlined in the 
Declaration on Human Rights Defenders, notably to article 5 point (b) and (c); and to 
article 6 point (b) and (c). 
</p>
<p>34. The Special Rapporteur is further concerned about information she has received 
regarding acts of violence, ill-treatment and intimidation compromising the physical and 
psychological integrity of human rights defenders in Bangladesh. In this regard, she would 
like to bring to the attention of the Government of Bangladesh the provisions contained in 
the Declaration on Human Rights Defenders, specifically article 2 and article 12, para. 2 
and 3. 
</p>
<p><b>  Belarus 
</b></p>
<p>35. JUA 22/12/10   Case no.: BLR 1/2010   State Reply: 10/01/11, 19/01/11   <b>Alleged 
arbitrary detention and torture related to the presidential elections of 19 December 
</b></p>
<p><b>2010</b>. 
</p>
<p>36. JUA 28/01/11   Case no.: BLR 1/2011   State Reply: 01/02/11   <b>Alleged 
intimidation against an NGO and interference in the work of lawyers in connection 
</b></p>
<p><b>with the 19 to 20 December 2010 demonstrations</b>. 
</p>
<p>37. JUA 25/02/11   Case no.: BLR 2/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged 
harassment, arrests and interrogation of human rights defenders</b>. 
</p>
<p>38. JAL 31/05/11   Case no.: BLR 6/2011   State Reply: 10/06/2011   <b>Alleged arrest 
and detention of human rights defender.</b> 
</p>
<p>39. JAL 01/06/2011   Case no.: BLR 7/2011   State Reply: 10/06/2011<b>   Alleged 
arrests, detentions and sentencing of human rights defenders following the 
</b></p>
<p><b>Presidential elections. </b> 
</p>
<p>40. JUA 15/08/11   Case no.: BLR 9/2011   State Reply: 31/10/11   <b>Alleged arrest and 
detention of human rights defender.</b> 
</p>
<p>41. JAL 21/11/11   Case no.: BLR 10/2011   State Reply: 17/01/12   <b>Allegation that 
legislative amendments may restrict the rights to freedom of peaceful assembly and of 
</b></p>
<p><b>association. 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Observations  
</b></p>
<p>42. The Special Rapporteur remains deeply concerned about developments in Belarus 
following the presidential elections of 19 December 2010, including reported restrictions on </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/19/55/Add.2 
</b></p>
<p> <b>9 
</b></p>
<p>non-governmental organizations, detention of human rights defenders who were protesting 
peacefully, and judicial harassment of human rights defenders. The Special Rapporteur 
reiterates her concern in the case of Mr. Ales Bialiatski, a human rights defender who was 
sentenced to 4.5 years in prison for financial irregularities on 25 November 2011 amid 
severe concerns regarding due process in relation to his trial. In this connection, the Special 
Rapporteur wishes to refer the Government of Belarus to the provisions outlined in the 
Declaration on Human Rights Defenders, notably to article 5 point (a); article 9, para. 1; 
and article 13. She remains available to provide any guidance and technical cooperation 
which the Government might request, and she reiterates her hope that the Government will 
respond favourably to her repeated requests since 2010 to visit the country.<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Brazil 
</b></p>
<p>43. JUA 23/03/11   Case no.: BRA 1/2011   State Reply: None to date<b>   Alleged killing 
of human rights defender and death threats against his family. 
</b></p>
<p>44. JAL 06/07/11   Case no.: BRA 3/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged killings 
of human rights defenders.  
</b></p>
<p>45. JUA<b> </b>11/07/11   Case no.: BRA 4/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged threats 
and attack against judge.  
</b></p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>46. The Special Rapporteur regrets that at the time of the finalization of this report, the 
Government had not transmitted a reply to her communications sent during the reporting 
period. The Special Rapporteur is deeply concerned about the physical and psychological 
integrity of human rights defenders in Brazil, in particular at reports of killings in the 
central and northern part of the country. In this connection, she wishes to refer the 
Government of Brazil to the provisions contained in the Declaration on Human Rights 
Defenders, specifically its article 2 and article 12, para. 2 and 3.<b> 
</b></p>
<p>47. The Special Rapporteur commends the measures put in place by the Government of 
Brazil to protect Ms. Fabiola Michele Moura but expresses concern that some of the 
measures reportedly do not respond adequately to the security risks in question. She wishes 
to refer the Government of Brazil to the recommendations contained in her report to the 
Human Rights Council in 2010 (A/HRC/13/22), para. 111 to 114. She remains available to 
provide any technical assistance the Government might require.<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Burundi 
</b></p>
<p>48. JAL 04/08/11   Case no.: BDI 1/2011   State Reply: 07/10/11   <b>All&#233;gations 
</b>d&#8223;assassinat d&#8223;un d&#233;fenseur  des droits de l&#8223;homme, d&#8223;insuffisances de la proc&#233;dure 
</p>
<p><b>judiciaire dans le cadre de cet assassinat et de menaces contre les membres de la 
</b></p>
<p><b>soci&#233;t&#233; civile qui ont d&#233;nonc&#233; cet assassinat et ces insuffisances. 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>49. La Rapporteuse reconna&#238;t les mesures entreprises par le Gouvernement afin 
d&#8217;amener les auteurs de l&#8217;assassinat d&#8217;Ernest Manirumwa devant la justice mais elle 
</p>
<p>regrette que le Gouvernement n&#8217;ait pas adress&#233; les inqui&#233;tudes de la soci&#233;t&#233; civile &#224; cet 
&#233;gard de fa&#231;on ad&#233;quate. Elle est &#233;galement pr&#233;occup&#233;e par les menaces all&#233;gu&#233;es &#224; 
l&#8217;int&#233;grit&#233; physique de certains d&#233;fenseurs des droits de l&#8217;homme au Burundi. A cet &#233;gard, 
</p>
<p>elle aimerait r&#233;f&#233;rer le Gouvernement du Burundi aux principes &#233;nonc&#233;s dans la </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/19/55/Add.2 
</b></p>
<p><b>10</b>  
</p>
<p>D&#233;claration sur les d&#233;fenseurs des droits de l&#8217;homme, notamment l&#8217;article 2 et l&#8217;article 12, 
</p>
<p>para. 2 et 3, ainsi que les recommandations fournies dans son rapport de 2010 au Conseil 
des droits de l&#8217;homme (A/HRC/13/22), para. 111 &#224; 114. La Rapporteuse sp&#233;ciale reste 
disponible pour fournir tout appui technique dont aurait besoin le Gouvernement.<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Cambodia 
</b></p>
<p>50. JAL 03/02/11   Case no.: KHM 1/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged 
conviction on defamation charges of human rights defenders.</b> 
</p>
<p>51. JAL 13/05/11   Case no.: KHM 3/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Allegation that 
draft NGO Law may hamper legitimate work in the promotion of human rights.</b> 
</p>
<p>52. JUA 23/09/11   Case no.: KHM 6/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged 
demolition of houses and police beating during the demolitions.</b> 
</p>
<p>53. JAL 26/09/11   Case no.: KHM 5/2011   State Reply 09/01/12, 23/01/12   <b>Alleged 
suspension, warnings and acts of intimidation against NGOs. 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Observations  
</b></p>
<p>54. The Special Rapporteur thanks the Government of Cambodia for the detailed 
response provided with regard to the communication regarding actions taken against civil 
society organizations. However, the Special Rapporteur regrets that at the time of the 
finalization of this report, the Government had not transmitted a reply to either of her other 
communications sent during the reporting period.  
</p>
<p>55. The Special Rapporteur reiterates her concern regarding the general situation for 
human rights defenders in Cambodia and reported acts of intimidation, arrests and judicial 
harassment as well as restrictions to their legitimate right to freedom of opinion and 
expression.  The Special Rapporteur urges the Government to take the necessary measures 
to ensure an environment which is conducive to the work of all human rights defenders 
allowing them to carry out their legitimate work without fear of persecution. In this regard, 
the Special Rapporteur commends the Government of Cambodia for consulting civil society 
during the development of the draft NGO law in the country. She encourages the 
Government to pay close attention to recommendations provided by civil society; the 
provisions contained in the Declaration on Human Rights Defenders; and the 
recommendations put forward in her 2009 report to the General Assembly (A/64/226), 
particularly para. 104 to 119. She remains available to provide any technical assistance the 
Government might require. 
</p>
<p><b>  Cameroon 
