<p><b>  Ethiopia 
</b></p>
<p>132. JUA 05/10/11   Case no.: ETH 4/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged arrests, 
detention and charges under antiterrorism legislation of journalists and opposition 
</b></p>
<p><b>politicians.</b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>133. The Special Rapporteur regrets that at the time of the finalization of this report, the 
Government had not transmitted a reply to her communication sent during the reporting 
period. The Special Rapporteur expresses deep concern regarding the alleged detention and 
charges brought against human rights defenders and, given the grave nature of the 
allegations received, she urges the Government to respond to the concerns raised by her. 
She is equally concerned about information received regarding the alleged use of anti-
terrorism legislation and NGO legislation in Ethiopia to restrict the right to freedom of 
association and the right to freedom of expression, which in consequence has impeded the 
work of human rights defenders. In this regard, the Special Rapporteur would like to 
remind the Government of Ethiopia of the provisions contained in the Declaration on 
Human Rights Defenders, specifically article 5, points b) and c), article 12 and article 13. 
Concerning the right to freedom of association, she urges Ethiopia to revisit her report to 
the General Assembly in 2009 (A/64/226), in particular recommendations given at para. 
104 through 116. She remains available to provide any technical assistance the Government 
of Ethiopia might require. 
</p>
