<p><b>  Observations   
</b></p>
<p>204. The Special Rapporteur wishes to express her concern at the reported increased 
restrictions to the activities of human rights defenders working in Israel, including arrests, 
administrative detentions and restrictions to their freedom of movement. She urges the 
Government of Israel to pay close attention to the provision contained in the Declaration on 
Human Rights Defenders, notably its articles 2 and 12.  
</p>
<p>205. The Special Rapporteur is also concerned about increased restrictions on human 
rights defenders&#8217; freedom of association and freedom of opinion and expression. In this 
regard, she wishes to call to the attention of the Government article 5, points b) and c), and 
article 6 of the Declaration on Human Rights Defenders, as well as the recommendations 
put forward in her report to the General Assembly in 2009 (A/64/226), para. 104 through 
</p><p>116. 
</p>
<p><b>  Kazakhstan 
</b></p>
<p>206. JUA 28/07/11   Case no.: KAZ 2/2011   State Reply: 17/09/11   <b>Alleged detention 
of human rights defender and trade unionist. </b> 
</p>
<p>207. JUA 03/10/11   Case no.: KAZ 4/2011   State Reply: None to date   <b>Alleged 
investigation, arrest and sentencing of human rights defenders. </b> 
</p>
<p><b>  Observations 
</b></p>
<p>208. The Special Rapporteur remains concerned about restrictions in place with regard to 
the freedoms of assembly and of opinion and expression in Kazakhstan, and about judicial 
harassment and sentencing of human rights defenders attempting to exercise these rights. 
She urges the Government to take the necessary measures to ensure the existence of an 
environment conducive to the work of human rights defenders allowing them to carry out 
their legitimate work without fear of persecution. In this regard, she wishes to remind the 
Government of Kazakhstan of the provisions contained in the Declaration on Human Rights 
Defenders, notably article 2, article 5, point a), article 6, points b) and c), article 9 and 
article 12. With regard to the right to freedom of assembly, she would also like to bring to 
the attention of the Government the recommendations put forward by the former Special 
Representative of the Secretary General on the situation of human rights defenders in her 
report to the General Assembly in 2006 (A/61/312, para. 98). 
</p>
<p>209. The Special Rapporteur reiterates her hope that the Government of Kazakhstan will 
respond favourably to her newly issued request to visit the country. She remains available 
to provide any technical support the Government might require. </p>

